== Reasons ==

Extreme poverty with an inability to afford raising a child is one of the reasons given for female infanticide in India.<ref name=rg1>{{cite journal | last1 = Giriraj | first1 = R. | year = 2004 | title = Changing Attitude to Female Infanticide in Salem | url = | journal = Journal of Social Welfare | volume = 50 | issue = 11| pages = 13–14 & 34–35 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Tandon | first1 = Sl | last2 = Sharma | first2 = R | year = 2006 | title = Female Foeticide and Infanticide in India: An Analysis of Crimes against Girl Children | url = | journal = International Journal of Criminal Justice Sciences | volume = 1 | issue = 1| pages = 1–7 }}</ref>{{clarify|reason=this might be a reason for infanticide but we need to explain why it is a reason for gender-specific infanticide|date=May 2015}} Such poverty has been a major reason for high infanticide rates in various cultures, throughout history, including England, France and India.<ref name="anagol"/><ref name="R Sauer 1978 pp. 81-93">{{cite journal | last1 = Sauer | first1 = R | year = 1978 | title = Infanticide and abortion in nineteenth-century Britain | url = | journal = Population Studies | volume = 32 | issue = 1| pages = 81–93 | doi=10.2307/2173842}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Kellum | first1 = B.A. | year = 1974 | title = Infanticide in England in the later Middle Ages | url = | journal = History of Childhood Quarterly | volume = 1 | issue = 3| pages = 367–88 }}</ref>

The dowry system in India is another reason that is given for female infanticide. Although India has taken steps to abolish the dowry system,{{sfnp|Parrot|Cummings|2006|p=160|ps=}} the practice persists, and for poorer families in rural regions female infanticide and gender selective abortion is attributed to the fear of being unable to raise a suitable dowry and then being socially ostracised.{{sfn|Oberman|2005|pp=5–6}}

Other major reasons given for infanticide, both female and male, include unwanted children, such as those conceived after rape, deformed children born to impoverished families, and those born to unmarried mothers lacking reliable, safe and affordable birth control.<ref name=rg1 /><ref>Christine Alder and Ken Polk, Child Victims of Homicide, Cambridge University Press, p. 4-5, {{ISBN|978-0-521-00251-6}}</ref>{{sfn | Hausfater | 2008 | pp=445–450 (Susan Scrimshaw)}} Relationship difficulties, low income, lack of support coupled with mental illness such as [[postpartum depression]] have also been reported as reasons for female infanticide in India.<ref name=cha1>Chandran et al (2002), Post-partum depression in a cohort of women from a rural area of Tamil Nadu, India: Incidence and risk factors, The British Journal of Psychiatry, 181(6), pp. 499–504</ref><ref>Chandra et al, Infanticidal ideas and infanticidal behavior in Indian women with severe postpartum psychiatric disorders, J Nerv Ment Dis. 2002 Jul, 190(7), pp. 457–61</ref><ref>{{Citation|pages=37–141|pmc=2174580|pmid=18188430|year=2007|author1=Hatters Friedman|first1=S|title=Child murder by mothers: Patterns and prevention|journal=World Psychiatry |volume=6|issue=3|last2=Resnick|first2=P. J.}}</ref>{{clarify|reason=this might be a reason for infanticide but we need to explain why it is a reason for gender-specific infanticide|date=May 2015}}

Elaine Rose in 1999 reported that disproportionately high female mortality is correlated to poverty, infrastructure and means to feed one's family, and that there has been an increase in the ratio of the probability that a girl survives to the probability that a boy survives with favourable rainfall each year and the consequent ability to irrigate farms in rural India.{{sfnp|Rose|1999|ps=}}

Ian Darnton-Hill et al. state that the effect of malnutrition, particularly micronutrient and vitamin deficiency, depends on sex, and it adversely impacts female infant mortality.<ref>Ian Darnton-Hill, Patrick Webb, Philip WJ Harvey, Joseph M Hunt, Nita Dalmiya, Mickey Chopra, Madeleine J Ball, Martin W Bloem and Bruno de Benoist, Micronutrient deficiencies and gender: social and economic costs, American Journal of Clinical Nutrition, May 2005, vol. 81, no. 5, pp. 1198S-1205S</ref>

== State response ==
In 1991 the [[Girl Child Protection Scheme]] was launched. This operates as a long-term financial incentive, with rural families having to meet certain obligations such as sterilisation of the mother. Once the obligations are met, the state puts aside {{INR}}2000 in a state-run fund. The fund, which should grow to {{INR}}10,000, is released to the daughter when she is 20: she can use it either to marry or to pursue higher education.{{sfnp|Perwez|2011|p=250-251|ps=}}

In 1992 the [[Government of India]] started the "baby cradle scheme". This allows families anonymously to give their child up for adoption without having to go through the formal procedure. The scheme has been praised for possibly saving the lives of thousands of baby girls but also criticised by human rights groups, who say that the scheme encourages child abandonment and also reinforces the low status in which women are held.{{sfnp|Bhalla|2012|ps=}} The scheme, which was piloted in [[Tamil Nadu]], saw cradles placed outside state-operated health facilities. The [[Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu]] added another incentive, giving money to families that had more than one daughter. 136 baby girls were given for adoption during the first four years of the scheme. In 2000, 1,218 cases of female infanticide were reported, the scheme was deemed a failure and it was abandoned. It was reinstated in the following year.{{sfnp|Parrot|Cummings|2006|pp=64–65|ps=}}

The 2011 census data showed a significant decline in the child sex ratio (CSR). Alarmed by the decline, the Government of India introduced [[Beti Bachao, Beti Padhao]] (BBBP) initiative. The program is intended to prevent gender discrimination and to ensure survival, protection and education of girls.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/beti-bachao-beti-padhao-programme-extended-to-all-640-districts-to-improve-child-sex-ratio/articleshow/61759269.cms|title='Beti Bachao Beti Padhao' programme extended to all 640 districts to improve child sex ratio - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-01-29}}</ref>

== International reactions ==

The [[Geneva Centre for the Democratic Control of Armed Forces]] (DCAF) wrote in their 2005 report, ''Women in an Insecure World'', that at a time when the number of casualties in war had fallen, a "secret genocide" was being carried out against women.{{sfn|Mashru|2012}} According to DCAF the demographic shortfall of women who have died for gender related issues is in the same range as the 191 million estimated dead from all conflicts in the 20th century.{{sfnp|Winkler|2005|p=7|ps=}} In 2012, the documentary ''[[It's a Girl: The Three Deadliest Words in the World]]'' was released. This focused on [[female infanticide in China]] and in India.{{sfnp|DeLugan|2013|pp=649–650|ps=}}

In 1991 [[Elisabeth Bumiller]] wrote ''May You be the Mother of a Hundred Sons: A Journey Among the Women of India'' around the subject of infanticide.{{sfn|Bumiller|1998|p=1}} In the chapter on female infanticide, titled ''No More Little Girls'', she said that the prevailing reason for the practice is "not as the act of monsters in a barbarian society but as the last resort of impoverished, uneducated women driven to do what they thought was best for themselves and their families."{{sfnp|Dehejia|1990|ps=}}

''Gift of A Girl Female Infanticide'' is a 1998 documentary that explores the prevalence of female infanticide in southern India, as well as steps which have been taken to help eradicate the practice. The documentary won an award from the [[Association for Asian Studies]].{{sfnp|Al-Malazi|1998|ps=}}{{sfnp|Merry|2008|ps=}}

